fn:normalize-space.notes:
The definition of whitespace is unchanged in [_Reference: xml11_]. It is repeated here
 for convenience:

 `S ::= (#x20 | #x9 | #xD | #xA)+`

fn:adjust-date-to-timezone.summary:
Adjusts an `xs:date` value to a specific timezone, or to no timezone at all;
 the result is the date in the target timezone that contains the starting instant of the
 supplied date.

op:subtract-times.rules:
The function returns the result of the expression:



```jsoniq
op-subtract-dateTimes(
 fn:dateTime(xs:date('1972-12-31'), $arg1),
 fn:dateTime(xs:date('1972-12-31'), $arg2))
```

fn:for-each.examples:
```jsoniq
fn:for-each(1 to 5, function($a) { $a * $a })
=> (1, 4, 9, 16, 25)
```

```jsoniq
fn:for-each(("john", "jane"),
 fn:string-to-codepoints#1)
=> (106, 111, 104, 110, 106, 97, 110, 101)
```

```jsoniq
fn:for-each(("23", "29"), xs:int#1)
=> (23, 29)
```

map:get.rules:
The function `map:get` attempts to find an entry within the *map* supplied as `$map` that has the *same key* as the supplied
 value of `$key`. If there is such an entry, it returns the associated value;
 otherwise it returns an empty sequence.

array:join.rules:
The function can be expressed as follows in XQuery:



```jsoniq
`
declare function array:join($arrays as array(*)*) as array(*) {
 if (fn:empty($arrays))
 then []
 else if (fn:count($arrays) eq 1)
 then $arrays
 else 
 op:array-concat(fn:head($arrays), array:join(fn:tail($arrays)))
};`
```

array:fold-right.rules:
The effect of the function is equivalent to the following recursive definition:



```jsoniq
if (array:size($array) eq 0)
then $zero
else $function( array:head($array), 
 array:fold-right(array:tail($array), $zero, $function) 
 )
```

fn:random-number-generator.examples:
The following example returns a random permutation of the integers in the range 1 to 100: 
 `fn:random-number-generator()?permute(1 to 100)`


 The following example returns a 10% sample of the items in an input sequence `$seq`, chosen at random: 
 `fn:random-number-generator()?permute($seq)[position() = 1 to (count($seq) idiv 10)]`


 The following code defines a function that can be called to produce a random sequence of `xs:double`
 values in the range zero to one, of specified length:



```jsoniq
declare %public function r:random-sequence($length as xs:integer) as xs:double* {
 r:random-sequence($length, fn:random-number-generator())
};

declare %private function r:random-sequence($length as xs:integer, 
 $G as map(xs:string, item())) {
 if ($length eq 0)
 then ()
 else ($G?number, r:random-sequence($length - 1, $G?next()))
};

r:random-sequence(200);
```
